  • Filling the empty string values with "empty"
  • one duplicate
  • id should be string
  • release_date should be datetime
  • Remove the series and miniseries into a separate table
  • Columns to be dropped(because we won't use them):

    • budget_adj
    • revenue_adj
    • overview
    • tagline

The given order is month/day/year. We can take the year from the release_year column

In [15]:
# Removing the last 2 characters (which indicate the year) and adding the year from the release_year column
movies['release_date'] = movies['release_date'].map(lambda x: x[:-2])
movies['release_date'] = movies['release_date'] + movies['release_year'].astype(str)

Conclusions¶

If you want to tackle the question of what are the best movies, you would have to look through different angles, for example, if you look at the popularity value of the movies you'll see that the following movies are the top 5

- Jurassic world 
- Mad max: fury road 
- Interstellar
- Guardians of the galaxy 
- Insurgent

However, if you look at it by the votes average, you'll get the following top 5:

- The story of film: an odyssey 
- The mask you live in 
- Black mirror: white christmas 
- Life cycles 
- Pink floyd: pulse

Addressed Question: Does the movie budget affect its popularity?¶

In [33]:
budgets = movies.nlargest(10, ['popularity']).budget
budgets = budgets/5e6 # Rescale the budgets
top_movies = movies.nlargest(10, ['popularity']).original_title
top_popularities = movies.popularity.sort_values(ascending=False).head(10)
In [34]:
#Preparing values for xticks plot
ind = np.arange(len(budgets))  # the x locations for the groups
width = 0.35       # the width of the bars
In [36]:
fig = plt.figure()
blue_bars = plt.bar(ind, budgets, width, color='b', alpha=.7, label='Budget')
yellow_bars = plt.bar(ind + width, top_popularities, width, color='y', alpha=.7, label='Popularity')

plt.xlabel('Movies')
plt.title('Budget & Popularity')
locations = ind + width / 2  
labels = top_movies
plt.xticks(locations, labels, fontsize=6, rotation=45)

plt.legend();
fig.savefig('Imgs/BudgetVsPopularity.png')

Conclusions:¶

As you can see from the graph, there's no certain correlation between movie popularity and its budget. As the popularity of the movie increases, the budget does not has a certain pattern, it sometimes increases and sometimes decreases.

Addressed Question: What are the budgets & Revenues of the most popular genres?¶

In [317]:
revenue_of_comedy = movies.query('genres == "Comedy"').groupby(['genres']).sum()['revenue']
revenue_of_drama = movies.query('genres == "Drama"').groupby(['genres']).sum()['revenue']
revenue_of_doc = movies.query('genres == "Documentary"').groupby(['genres']).sum()['revenue']
revenue_of_horror = movies.query('genres == "Horror" or genres == "Horror|Thriller"').groupby(['genres']).sum()['revenue']

budget_of_comedy = movies.query('genres == "Comedy"').groupby(['genres']).sum()['budget']
budget_of_drama = movies.query('genres == "Drama"').groupby(['genres']).sum()['budget']
budget_of_doc = movies.query('genres == "Documentary"').groupby(['genres']).sum()['budget']
budget_of_horror = movies.query('genres == "Horror" or genres == "Horror|Thriller"').groupby(['genres']).sum()['budget']

fig = plt.figure()
plt.bar(['Comedy'], revenue_of_comedy, alpha=0.5)
plt.bar(['Drama'], revenue_of_drama, alpha=0.5)
plt.bar(['Horror'], revenue_of_horror, alpha=0.5)
plt.bar(['Documentary'], revenue_of_doc, alpha=0.5)

plt.bar(['Comedy'], budget_of_comedy, alpha=0.5)
plt.bar(['Drama'], budget_of_drama, alpha=0.5)
plt.bar(['Horror'], budget_of_horror, alpha=0.5)
plt.bar(['Documentary'], budget_of_doc, alpha=0.5)

plt.xticks(fontsize=8)
plt.title("Revenues & Budgets of the Best Genres")
plt.show();
fig.savefig('Imgs/Revenues&BudgetsOfGenres.png')

Conclusions¶

The graph shows that the best and most popular genres have high budgets and revenues in the same order as their popularity.

Limitations of the dataset¶

  • The dataset has movies until the year 2015

  • Only 0.1% of the dataset has average vote above 8.5

  • The dataset regards the cast of the movie as one string

  • The dataset contains many empty values

  • 75% of the budgets and revenues are zero values

In [ ]:
